{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478816"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:16:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18848"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18848"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.04,0.02,0,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11581"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79695"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11581"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64999"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5456"},{"type":"tags","id":"9660"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"10785"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27252"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79695"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-day-old newborn is in the hospital nursery after an uncomplicated delivery. The baby appears healthy, with no significant medical history. The parents are first-time parents and have questions about the newborn screening test that was performed shortly after birth. They are particularly interested in understanding the purpose of this screening and what conditions it aims to detect.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary purpose of newborn screening?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["To screen for conditions that can be treated early to prevent serious health problems","To identify genetic predispositions to common diseases","To detect conditions that require immediate surgical intervention","To diagnose congenital heart defects","To assess the overall health and development of the newborn"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary purpose of newborn screening is to \u003Cstrong\u003Escreen for conditions that can be treated early to prevent serious health problems\u003C/strong\u003E. This public health program is designed to identify newborns at risk for certain genetic, metabolic, hormonal, and functional conditions that are not apparent at birth. Early detection allows for timely intervention, which can significantly improve outcomes and prevent severe health issues or even death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiagnosing congenital heart defects\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary aim of newborn screening, although some programs may include pulse oximetry to screen for critical congenital heart disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdentifying genetic predispositions to common diseases\u003C/strong\u003E is not the focus of newborn screening, as it targets specific conditions that require immediate attention rather than predispositions to diseases that may develop later in life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetecting conditions that require immediate surgical intervention\u003C/strong\u003E is not the main goal of newborn screening. The conditions screened for are typically those that can be managed medically or through dietary modifications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAssessing the overall health and development of the newborn\u003C/strong\u003E is not the purpose of newborn screening. While it provides important information about specific conditions, it does not evaluate the general health or developmental status of the infant.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Newborn screening is a public health program aimed at the early identification of conditions that can affect a child\u0027s long-term health or survival.","The conditions screened for vary by country and region, but typically include metabolic, endocrine, and genetic disorders.","Early detection through newborn screening allows for timely intervention, which can prevent severe health problems or even death."],"references":["Therrell BL, Padilla CD, Borrajo GJC, Khneisser I, Schielen PCJI, Knight-Madden J, Malherbe HL, Kase M. Current Status of Newborn Bloodspot Screening Worldwide 2024: A Comprehensive Review of Recent Activities (2020-2023). Int J Neonatal Screen. 2024 May 23;10(2):38. doi: 10.3390/ijns10020038. PMID: 38920845; PMCID: PMC11203842."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64999"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18848"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64999"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T13:01:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T13:03:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11581"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79695"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app